The diagram shows two $5$-by-$5$ squares.  The inner four triangles are congruent isosceles triangles.  What is the length of the segment which is furthest from the large square?

What I have tried: I have tried to add the dimensions I know to find the distance, but that got me no where. Since  we have three $1\times1$ internal squares, there must be a different distance. Furthermore, there must be two congruent sides parallel to the horizontal length of the external square, and therefore all of the other length must be parallel to this square. Finally, if we examine the triangle on that right hand side, its hypotenuse must be an integer amount of 5 or greater in order to fit into the small squares in the first quadrant. If it is 5 long, then all of its perpendicular sides must therefore be $\frac{5}{\sqrt2}$. By similar logic, one side of the larger triangle on the other side of the picture must be $5\sqrt2$.

How do I work my way from here? We can apply the Pythagorean Theorem here to compute $PA$, and you'll verify that $$PA^2 = 687-404\sqrt{5} \tag1.$$ Now observe that the center of the large square is the midpoint of $\overline{PA}$, since 
$\overline{PA}$ partitions the smaller square itself into equal halves. Since its area is $25$, the side length of the smallest square is $\sqrt{25/2} = 5/ \sqrt{2} = 5\sqrt{2}/2$. Let this smaller square have center $O$. Then $$PO^2 + OA^2 = PA^2 \implies PO^2 + 25/2 = 2(687-404\sqrt{5}) $$ and hence $$PO = \sqrt{2(687-404\sqrt{5}) – 25/2} = \sqrt{2 \times 42.5 – 25/2} = \sqrt{85 – 25/2} = \sqrt{(42.5) \times (4)} = \sqrt{170} = \sqrt{85} \text{(Hint: } 170=85\times 2)$$ Note: When you are not certain how expressions with radicals are behaving, it helps to write the fractional exponents as radicals. For example, we write
$$\sqrt[n]{a} = a^{\frac{1}{n}}.$$

