Let $a,$ $b,$ and $c$ denote the three distinct positive integers that serve as the roots of the equation $x^3 - 7x^2 + kx - m = 0.$</think>
Consider the function
\[f(x) = x^3 - 7x^2 + kx - m.\]The three roots of $f(x)$ are $a,$ $b,$ and $c.$ Hence \[f(x) = (x - a)(x - b)(x - c) = x^3 - (a + b + c)x^2 + (ab + bc + ca)x - abc.\]Equate the coefficients and derive three new equations;
\begin{align*}
a + b + c &= 7,\\ab + ac + bc &= k,\\abc &= m.\end{align*}Suppose that $a \le b \le c.$ Then $a,$ $b,$ and $c$ must all be positive integers $\le 6,$ because $a,$ $b,$ and $c$ cannot be greater than $7$ by the first equation. Because $a + b + c = 7,$ weights $a,$ $b,$ and $c$ must be about the same size, so there are only two reasonable arrangements of the three integer weights: $(1)$ $a < b < c$ and $(2)$ $a = b \le c.$ In fact, by manipulating the order of $a,$ $b,$ and $c,$ it is not difficult to see that case $(1)$ always occurs. Hence \begin{align*}a + b + c &= 7,\\a + b \le c + c = 2c,\\ab + ac + bc = k,\\abc &= m.\end{align*}Using the first inequality, it follows that \[2c \ge a + b + c = 7,\]so $c \ge \frac72,$ which implies that $c = 4$ or $c = 3.$ Note that $c = 4$ is not possible because it would imply $6 \le a + b \le 5,$ which is impossible since $a$ and $b$ are both positive integers. Hence $c = 3.$ In that case, $a + b = 4.$ Since $a \le b,$ it follows that $a = b = 2.$ The mean of $a,$ $b,$ and $c$ is $4/3.$ According to Vieta, the arithmetic mean of the roots of $f(x)$ is $7/3.$ Hence \[\frac43 \cdot \frac{x}{a + b + c} = \frac73 \cdot \frac{m}{abc}\] \[\frac{x}{abc} + \frac{m}{abc} = \frac{7m}{4abc}\] \[\frac{x + m}{abc} = \frac{7m}{4(ab + ac + bc)} = \frac{7m}{72}.\]Now $\frac{m}{abc}$ must be positive, but must also be $\le 1$ because $a,$ $b,$ and $c$ serve as weights on the right side of the expression $\frac{m}{abc}.$ Hence \[\frac{m}{abc} \le \frac{7m}{72} \le 1,\]which implies that $m \le 12.$ According to Vieta, $abc = m,$ so $1 \le abc \le 12.$ The only distinct positive integers $a,$ $b,$ and $c$ such that $a + b + c = 7$ and $abc \le 12$ are $2,$ $2,$ and $3.$ That is, the three roots of $f(x)$ are $2,$ $2,$ and $3,$ which implies that $k = 2 \cdot 2 + 2 \cdot 3 + 2 \cdot 3 = 16.$ With $k$ and $m$ known, it follows that \[k + m = 16 + 12 = \boxed{28}.\]
</think> $k + m = 28$ <answer>

